  <datafield tag="500" ind1=" " ind2=" ">
    <subfield code="a">Evelina A. S. Smith has heard very good accounts of the New York and Boston anti-slavery meetings, but she thinks that the New Hampshire meeting at Concord &quot;entirely failed of the intended effect.&quot; She refers to &quot;absurdities committed in Boston on the 17th.&quot; President Tyler &quot;insulted us by bringing a slave here.&quot; Daniel Webster &quot;was evidently crippled, I think, [by his knowledge of conditions] for his speech was a poor affair.&quot; Mr. Oliver Stearns, the Hingham minister, has grown conservative in respect to slavery since Miss [Abby] Kelley was here and in religion since Mr. Theodore Parker was here. Mr. Increase S. Smith has been turned out of the Sunday school. Evelina A. S. Smith says: &quot;... the Baptists are very zealous, the Episcopalians are getting up a society, &amp; in fact, to use a much abused expression, every one is inquiring what shall I do to be saved. In all this I have no part or lot &amp; feel that it is all sham.&quot;</subfield>
  </datafield>
